Hi all,

one step closer. My tests have shown that if you send a .tar archive which has a subfolder with files inside (e.g. a tarball you may receive from github's api call) the "context directory" is not extended by that path.
Even when explicitly specified, it will work for the "Dockerfile" itself but not for any other.

IMO this is a bug (or missing piece of code) as the documentation states:
`If no context directory is specified, then Podman will assume the current working directory as the build context, which should contain the Containerfile.`

To reproduce the situation, get the current tarball from github:
`curl -v -L https://github.com/blindshare/simpleCherryPyPage/tarball/master > simpleTest.tar`

Use this podman API call and try to build the image:
`curl -X POST --header "Content-Type: application/x-tar" --data-binary @/data/work/simpletest/simpleTest.tar -v http://192.168.0.3:2345/v3.0.0/libpod/build?dockerfile=blindshare-simpleCherryPyPage-fa80160/`

The "dockerfile" will be found and podman starts to create the image ... until ...
```
{"stream":"STEP 8: COPY ./simple.py /opt/simpleTest\n"}
{"error":"error building at STEP \"COPY ./simple.py /opt/simpleTest\": checking on sources under \"/var/tmp/libpod_builder467105738/build\": copier: stat: \"/simple.py\": no such file or directory\n"}
```

Now go back to the dir where you've downloaded the .tar file. Extract it and create a new .tar that contains only the Dockerfile and page.py - with no sub-directory !
Retry to build the image:
`curl -X POST --header "Content-Type: application/x-tar" --data-binary @/data/work/simpletest/noSubDir-simpleTest.tar -v http://192.168.0.3:2345/v3.0.0/libpod/build`

... all works fine:
```
{"stream":"STEP 8: COPY simple.py /opt/simpleTest\n"}
{"stream":"STEP 9: CMD [\"/usr/bin/python3\", \"/opt/simpleTest/simple.py\"]\n"}
{"stream":"STEP 10: COMMIT\n"}
{"stream":"Getting image source signatures\n"}
{"stream":"Copying blob sha256:30d61bb737bb9be7178afce441d0ca5098909a59001a0301d3b50544e659ace1\n"}
{"stream":"Copying blob sha256:019739e07a3bb0d9b67701b7530324e24ea75eaa081a15fc0f5f2941c04c951e\n"}
{"stream":"Copying config sha256:7061c04398c65e993156914b6afc2791da15365165ca871e47154565a3836675\n"}
{"stream":"Writing manifest to image destination\n"}
{"stream":"Storing signatures\n"}
```

@blindshare I dont think that param `dockerfile` specifies that you are changing path to build context instead docker doc says `Path within the build context to the Dockerfile.` i think build context is always root of the exploded tar.

Ref: https://docs.docker.com/engine/api/v1.41/#operation/ImageBuild

I'll verify this against docker if docker allows us to change context then i think we should otherwise in the interest of keeping parity we could mark this as `WONTFIX` and instead explore adding a new parameter of `buildContextPath`

@blindshare as expected I tried with docker `engine/api/v1.41` and it has behavior as documented

Here is directory structure inside tar
```console
.
├── file
│   ├── Dockerfile
│   └── hello.sh
└── parentdirectory
```
and API call fails for 
```console
sudo curl -s --unix-socket /var/run/docker.sock -X POST --header "Content-Type: application/x-tar" --data-binary @/home/flouthoc/docker-exp/file.tar.gz http:/1.41/build?dockerfile=file/Dockerfile
{"stream":"Step 1/4 : FROM ubuntu:16.04"}
{"stream":"\n"}
{"stream":" ---\u003e b6f507652425\n"}
{"stream":"Step 2/4 : RUN mkdir test"}
{"stream":"\n"}
{"stream":" ---\u003e Using cache\n"}
